#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:1
msgid "What Soundness Means for an OS Framework"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:3
msgid "The Soundness Goal"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:5
msgid "The soundness of OSTD provides the following strong guarantee:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:7
msgid ""
"**No sequence of calls to OSTD's safe public API — combined with any "
"behavior from user-space programs and peripheral devices — from a client in "
"safe Rust can trigger undefined behaviors (UBs).**"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:11
msgid ""
"Note that soundness is distinct from correctness. A sound OSTD may still "
"contain logic bugs (e.g., a scheduler that starves tasks, or an allocator "
"that wastes memory). Soundness means these bugs cannot escalate into memory "
"corruption, data races, type confusion, or any other form of UB. The OS may "
"crash, deadlock, or behave incorrectly — but it will never silently corrupt "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:19
msgid "Three Levels of Undefined Behavior"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:21
msgid ""
"An OS kernel faces undefined behavior (UB) threats that ordinary Rust "
"programs do not. We classify them into three levels:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:24
msgid ""
"**Language-level UB.** These are the UB categories defined by the [Rust "
"Reference](https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/behavior-considered-undefined."
"html): data races, use-after-free, dangling pointers, null pointer "
"dereference, type confusion, aliasing violations (breaking the \"shared XOR "
"mutable\" rule), and reading uninitialized memory. Rust's safe subset "
"prevents all of these at compile time. OSTD must ensure that its `unsafe` "
"code does not reintroduce them."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:32
msgid ""
"**Environment-level UB.** Programming languages make implicit assumptions "
"about their execution environment: the stack is valid, the heap is not "
"corrupted, and the code being executed has not been overwritten. In a "
"kernel, these assumptions must be actively maintained. A stack overflow that "
"jumps over a guard page, a heap corruption from a faulty allocator, or a "
"code page overwritten by a rogue DMA transfer can all silently violate these "
"assumptions."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:42
msgid ""
"**Architecture-level UB.** OS kernels directly manipulate hardware state: "
"CPU control registers, page tables, interrupt descriptor tables, IOMMU "
"configuration. Incorrect manipulation can corrupt the execution environment "
"in ways invisible to the Rust compiler. For example: misconfiguring a page "
"table can cause the CPU to write kernel data to the wrong physical address; "
"allowing a device to DMA into a page table page can corrupt address "
"translation; improperly saving/restoring CPU registers across context "
"switches can corrupt task state."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:54
msgid "OSTD must defend against all three levels simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:56
msgid ""
"\\[!NOTE\\] To be concrete, our soundness analysis targets the x86-64 CPU "
"architecture, but our arguments can be generalized to other CPU "
"architectures."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:60
msgid "The Trust Model"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:62
msgid "The following components are trusted — their correctness is assumed:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:64
msgid ""
"**The Rust compiler and core libraries** (`rustc`, `core`, `alloc`). We rely "
"on the compiler to correctly enforce Rust's safety guarantees for safe code "
"and to correctly compile `unsafe` code according to the language "
"specification."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:68
msgid ""
"**OSTD itself**. This is the subject of this document: we argue that OSTD's "
"`unsafe` code is sound."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:72
msgid ""
"**The bootloader and firmware**. We trust the bootloader to load the kernel "
"correctly, provide accurate memory maps, and configure the initial page "
"table. We trust firmware (ACPI tables, device trees) to accurately describe "
"the hardware."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:77
msgid ""
"**Core hardware**: the CPU (correct instruction execution, correct privilege "
"level enforcement, correct page table walks), memory controller (correct "
"physical memory access), and IOMMU (correct DMA remapping and interrupt "
"remapping when enabled)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:82
msgid ""
"The following components are **not** trusted — OSTD must remain sound "
"regardless of their behavior:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:85
msgid ""
"**All OS services in `kernel/`**. These are written in safe Rust. They may "
"contain logic bugs (incorrect syscall implementations, file system "
"corruption, network protocol violations) but cannot cause UB. This includes "
"all device drivers, file systems, networking stacks, process management, and "
"IPC."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:93
msgid ""
"**Injected policies**: task schedulers, frame allocators, and slab "
"allocators. These are registered by OS services via safe traits. They may "
"make arbitrarily bad decisions (schedule the same task twice, return an "
"already-allocated frame, return a misaligned slab slot) but cannot cause UB. "
"OSTD's mechanisms enforce soundness independently of policy correctness "
"([Safe Policy Injection](safe-policy-injection.md))."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:102
msgid ""
"**User-space programs**. They may execute arbitrary instructions, make "
"arbitrary system calls with arbitrary arguments, and attempt to corrupt "
"kernel state through any user-accessible mechanism. OSTD must ensure that "
"user-space behavior cannot cause kernel UB."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/what-soundness-means.md:108
msgid ""
"**Peripheral devices** (NICs, GPUs, disks, USB devices). They may issue "
"arbitrary DMA transfers to any physical address, generate arbitrary "
"interrupts, and return arbitrary data in response to MMIO/PIO reads. OSTD "
"must ensure that peripheral behavior cannot corrupt kernel memory safety. "
"This is enforced by the IOMMU ([Safe Kernel-Peripheral Interactions](safe-"
"kernel-peripheral-interactions.md)) and the typed/untyped memory model "
"([Safe Physical Memory Management](safe-memory-management.md))."
msgstr ""

