#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:1
msgid "Concurrency and Races"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:3
msgid ""
"Concurrency code is reviewed with extreme rigor. Lock ordering, atomic "
"correctness, memory ordering, and race condition analysis are all demanded "
"explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:7
msgid "Establish and enforce a consistent lock order (`lock-ordering`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:9
msgid ""
"Acquiring two locks in different orders from different code paths is a "
"potential deadlock. Hierarchical lock order must be established and "
"documented."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:19
msgid "// Lock order: group of process -> session inner -> job control\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:25
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2942](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2942)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:28
msgid ""
"Never do I/O or blocking operations while holding a spinlock (`no-io-under-"
"spinlock`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:30
msgid ""
"Holding a spinlock while performing I/O or blocking operations is a deadlock "
"hazard. Use a sleeping mutex or restructure to drop the lock first."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:36
msgid "// Good — spinlock dropped before I/O\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:38
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:44
msgid "// state: SpinLock<...>\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:42
msgid "// Bad — I/O while holding spinlock\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:48
msgid "See also: PR [\\#925](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/925)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:51
msgid "Do not use atomics casually (`careful-atomics`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:53
msgid ""
"When multiple atomic fields must be updated in concert, use a lock. Only use "
"atomics when a single value is genuinely independent."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:59
msgid "// Good — a lock protects correlated fields\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:67
msgid ""
"// Bad — two atomics that must be consistent\n"
"// but can be observed in an inconsistent state\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:76
msgid ""
"Critical sections must not be split across lock boundaries (`atomic-critical-"
"sections`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:78
msgid ""
"Operations that must be atomic (check + conditional action) must happen "
"under the same lock acquisition. Moving a comparison outside the critical "
"region is a correctness bug."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:85
msgid "// Good — check and action under the same lock\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:91
msgid ""
"// Bad — TOCTOU race: state can change\n"
"// between the check and the action\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/concurrency-and-races.md:101
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2277](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2277)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/defensive-programming.md:1
msgid "Defensive Programming"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/defensive-programming.md:3
msgid ""
"Assertions verify invariants that must hold for the program to be correct. "
"Choosing the right assertion type balances safety against runtime cost."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/defensive-programming.md:8
msgid "Use `debug_assert` for correctness-only checks (`debug-assert`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/defensive-programming.md:10
msgid ""
"Assertions verifying invariants that should never fail in correct code "
"belong in `debug_assert!`, not `assert!`. `debug_assert!` is compiled out in "
"release builds, so the check catches bugs during development without costing "
"anything in production."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/defensive-programming.md:22
msgid ""
"See also: [std::debug_assert!](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/macro."
"debug_assert.html) and [Rust Reference: `debug_assertions`](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/reference/conditional-compilation.html#debug_assertions)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:1
msgid "Error Handling"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust's error handling model — `Result`, `?`, and typed errors — is central "
"to writing reliable kernel code."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:6
msgid "Propagate errors with `?` (`propagate-errors`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:8
msgid ""
"Use the `?` operator to propagate errors idiomatically. In kernel code, `."
"unwrap()` is rejected wherever failure is a legitimate possibility."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:15
msgid "// Good — propagate with ?\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:18
msgid "// Bad — unwrap hides the failure path\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/error-handling.md:23
msgid ""
"See also: _The Rust Programming Language_, Chapter 9 \"Error Handling\" and "
"[Rust by Example: unpacking options and defaults with `?`](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/rust-by-example/std/result/question_mark.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:1
msgid "Logging"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:3
msgid ""
"Consistent logging makes debugging tractable across a large kernel codebase."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:6
msgid "Use OSTD logging macros exclusively (`ostd-log-only`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:8
msgid ""
"All OSTD-based crates must use the logging macros provided by the [`ostd::"
"log`](https://asterinas.github.io/ostd/ostd/log/) module: `debug!`, `info!`, "
"`notice!`, `warn!`, `error!`, `crit!`, `alert!`, `emerg!`. Import them via "
"`use ostd::prelude::*` or `use ostd::log::{info, warn, ...}`."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:15
msgid ""
"Do not use the third-party [`log`](https://docs.rs/log) crate directly. OSTD "
"provides a bridge that forwards messages from third-party crates (e.g., "
"`smoltcp`) that use `log`, but first-party code must use OSTD's macros."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:20
msgid ""
"Custom output functions, `println!`, and hand-rolled serial print macros are "
"not acceptable in production code. Exception: code that runs before the "
"logging subsystem is initialized may use early-boot output helpers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:28
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:31
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:34
msgid "\"VirtIO block device initialized: {} sectors\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:29
msgid "// Bad — using the log crate directly\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:32
msgid "// Bad — using println\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:39
msgid "Choose appropriate log levels (`log-levels`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:41
msgid ""
"OSTD provides eight log levels matching the severity levels described in "
"[`syslog(2)`](https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/syslog.2.html):"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:44
msgid "Level"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:44
msgid "Use for"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:46
msgid "`emerg!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:46
msgid "System is unusable; immediately before `abort()`."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:47
msgid "`alert!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:47
msgid "Action must be taken immediately."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:48
msgid "`crit!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:48
msgid "Critical conditions: unrecoverable resource exhaustion."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:49
msgid "`error!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:49
msgid "Serious but recoverable failures: invariant violations, I/O errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:50
msgid "`warn!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:50
msgid "Recoverable problems: fallback paths taken, deprecated usage detected."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:51
msgid "`notice!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:51
msgid "Normal but significant events: CPU online, security feature activated."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:52
msgid "`info!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:52
msgid ""
"Routine informational events: subsystem initialization, configuration "
"changes."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:53
msgid "`debug!`"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:53
msgid ""
"Development diagnostics: state transitions, intermediate values, per-packet "
"tracing."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/logging.md:55
msgid ""
"Use `error!` for failures that the system can recover from. Use `crit!` or "
"`emerg!` only for failures immediately before a halt or abort. A log "
"statement that fires on every syscall or every timer tick must use `debug!`."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:1
msgid "Memory and Resource Management"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust's ownership model is the primary tool for safe resource management in "
"the kernel."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:6
msgid "Use RAII for all resource acquisition and release (`raii`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:8
msgid ""
"Resources — IRQ enable/disable state, port numbers, file handles, DMA "
"buffers, lock guards — must use the `Drop` trait for automatic cleanup. "
"Manual `enable()`/`disable()` call pairs are rejected."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:14
msgid "// Good — RAII guard ensures IRQs are re-enabled\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:22
msgid "// Bad — caller can forget to re-enable\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:28
msgid ""
"Prefer lexical lifetimes so the Rust compiler inserts `drop` automatically, "
"rather than calling `drop()` manually. When the default drop order is "
"incorrect, use explicit `drop()` calls."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/memory-and-resource-management.md:34
msgid "See also: PR [\\#164](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/164)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:1
msgid "Performance"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:3
msgid ""
"Performance on critical paths is taken very seriously. Changes to hot paths "
"must be benchmarked. Unnecessary copies, allocations, and O(n) algorithms "
"are rejected."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:8
msgid "Avoid O(n) algorithms on hot paths (`no-linear-hot-paths`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:10
msgid ""
"System call dispatch, scheduler enqueue, and frequent query operations must "
"not introduce O(n) complexity where n is a quantity that can be large "
"(number of processes, number of file descriptors, etc.). Demand sub-linear "
"alternatives."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:18
msgid "// Bad — O(n) scan on every enqueue\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:22
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:29
msgid "\"at least one CPU\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:25
msgid ""
"// Good — maintain a priority queue\n"
"// so selection is O(log n)\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:33
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1790](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/1790)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:36
msgid "Minimize unnecessary copies and allocations (`minimize-copies`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:38
msgid ""
"Extra data copies — serializing to a stack buffer before writing, cloning an "
"`Arc` when a `&` reference suffices, collecting into a `Vec` when an "
"iterator would do — should be avoided."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:45
msgid "// Bad — unnecessary Arc::clone\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:50
msgid "// Good — borrow when ownership is not needed\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:57
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2582](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2582) and "
"[\\#2725](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2725)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:61
msgid ""
"No premature optimization without evidence (`no-premature-optimization`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/select-topics/performance.md:63
msgid ""
"Performance optimizations must be justified with data. Introducing "
"complexity to solve a non-existent problem is rejected. If you claim a "
"change improves performance, show the numbers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:1
msgid "Testing Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:3
msgid ""
"This page covers language-agnostic testing conventions. For Rust-specific "
"assertion policy (`assert!` vs `debug_assert!`), see [Rust Guidelines — "
"Defensive Programming](rust-guidelines/select-topics/defensive-programming."
"md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:7
msgid "Add regression tests for every bug fix (`add-regression-tests`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:9
msgid ""
"When a bug is fixed, a test that would have caught the bug should accompany "
"the fix. Include a reference to the issue number in a comment so future "
"readers can recover the original context."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:15
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2962](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2962)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:18
msgid "Test user-visible behavior, not internals (`test-visible-behavior`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:20
msgid ""
"Tests should validate observable, user-facing outcomes. Prefer testing "
"through public APIs rather than exposing internal constants in test code."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:24
msgid ""
"Name tests after the behavior or specification concept being verified, not "
"after internal implementation details. Using kernel-internal names in user-"
"space regression tests creates unnecessary coupling."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:29
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2926](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2926)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:32
msgid "Use assertion macros, not manual inspection (`use-assertions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:34
msgid ""
"Use language- or framework-provided assertion helpers instead of printing "
"values and manually inspecting output. Assertions provide clear failure "
"messages and make tests self-checking."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:39
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2877](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2877) and "
"[\\#2926](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2926)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:43
msgid "Clean up resources after every test (`test-cleanup`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:45
msgid ""
"Always clean up resources after a test: close file descriptors, unlink "
"temporary files, and call `waitpid` on child processes. Leftover resources "
"can cause flaky failures in subsequent tests."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:52
msgid "// Good — cleanup after use\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:53
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:56
msgid "\"/tmp/test_file\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:53
msgid "// ... test logic ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/testing-guidelines.md:59
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2926](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2926) and "
"[\\#2969](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2969)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:3
msgid "Define sections"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:5
msgid ""
"To define built-in sections, such as the text section, it is preferable to "
"use the short directive, e.g., `.text`. For other sections, the section "
"directive with the desired flags and type should be used, e.g., `.section \"."
"bsp_boot\", \"awx\", @progbits`."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:11
msgid ""
"To ensure consistency and clarity, a blank line should follow each section "
"definition, creating a separate code block for each definition."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:14
msgid ""
"```asm\n"
".section \".bsp_boot.stack\", \"aw\", @nobits\n"
"\n"
"boot_stack_bottom:\n"
"    .align 4096\n"
"    .skip 0x40000  # 256 KiB\n"
"boot_stack_top:\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:23
msgid ""
"In x86-64, if an executable section contains only 64-bit code, the `.code64` "
"directive should be placed directly after the section definition. The same "
"applies to the `.code32` directive for 32-bit code."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:36
msgid "Define functions"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:38
msgid ""
"Function attributes, such as `.global` and `.align`, should be placed "
"directly before the function. These function attributes should not be "
"indented."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:49
msgid ""
"The assembler treats the directives `.global` and `.globl` as the same. For "
"clarity, however, `.global` is preferred."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:52
msgid ""
"Note that a Rust crate is a single translation unit, so `global_asm!` labels "
"in different modules within the same crate share the same global namespace. "
"In RISC-V, we have experienced that defining two labels with the same name "
"in different modules can nondeterministically cause duplicate symbol error. "
"The `.L` prefix does not help. Therefore, add custom prefixes to your labels "
"to avoid name clashes. Nevertheless, use `.global` to export symbols that "
"need to be visible within the same crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:59
msgid ""
"In x86-64, if an executable section contains a mix of 32-bit and 64-bit "
"code, the `.code64` and `.code32` directives are treated as function "
"attributes."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:75
msgid ""
"Functions that can be called from Rust code should also include the `.type` "
"and `.size` directives. This will give debuggers a better understanding of "
"the function. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:87
msgid ""
"Note that this rule explicitly limits the functions to those that can be "
"called from Rust code. Therefore, it does not apply to boot entry points, "
"exception trampolines, or interrupt trampolines. They may not fit into the "
"typical definition of \"function\", and their sizes may be ill-defined."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:3
msgid "API Documentation Guidelines"
msgstr "API 文档指南"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:5
msgid ""
"API documentation describes the meanings and usage of APIs, and will be "
"rendered into web pages by rustdoc."
msgstr "API 文档描述了 API 的含义和用法，并将由 rustdoc 渲染成网页。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:8
msgid ""
"It is necessary to add documentation to all public APIs, including crates, "
"modules, structs, traits, functions, macros, and more. The use of the "
"`#[warn(missing_docs)]` lint enforces this rule."
msgstr ""
"所有公共 API，包括 crate、模块、结构体、trait、函数、宏等等，都必须添加文"
"档。 `#[warn(missing_docs)]` lint 会强制执行此规则。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:12
msgid ""
"Asterinas adheres to the API style guidelines of the Rust community. The "
"recommended API documentation style are specified by two official resources:"
msgstr ""
"Asterinas 遵循 Rust 社区的 API 风格指南。推荐的 API 文档风格由两个官方资源指"
"定："

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:14
msgid ""
"The rustdoc book: [How to write documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"rustdoc/how-to-write-documentation.html);"
msgstr ""
"The rustdoc book: [How to write documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"rustdoc/how-to-write-documentation.html)；"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:15
msgid ""
"The Rust RFC book: [API Documentation Conventions](https://rust-lang.github."
"io/rfcs/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.html#appendix-a-full-"
"conventions-text)."
msgstr ""
"The Rust RFC book: [API Documentation Conventions](https://rust-lang.github."
"io/rfcs/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.html#appendix-a-full-"
"conventions-text)。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:17
msgid "Lint Guidelines"
msgstr "Lint 指南"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:19
msgid ""
"Lints help us improve the code quality and find more bugs. When suppressing "
"lints, the suppression should affect as little scope as possible, to make "
"readers aware of the exact places where the lint is generated, and to make "
"it easier for subsequent committers to maintain such lint."
msgstr ""
"代码检查工具 Lints 帮助我们提高代码质量并发现更多漏洞。在抑制代码检查时，应尽"
"可能缩小影响范围，以便让读者清楚了解代码检查产生的具体位置，也便于后续提交者"
"维护此类代码检查。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:24
msgid ""
"For example, if some methods in a trait are dead code, marking the entire "
"trait as dead code is unnecessary and can easily be misinterpreted as the "
"trait itself being dead code. Instead, the following pattern is preferred:"
msgstr ""
"例如，如果某个 trait 中的某些方法是死代码，则没有必要将整个 trait 标记为死代"
"码，而且很容易被误解为 trait 本身就是死代码。相反，建议采用以下模式："

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:40
msgid ""
"There is one exception: If it is clear enough that every member will trigger "
"the lint, it is reasonable to expect the lint at the type level. For "
"example, in the following code, we add `#[expect(non_camel_case_types)]` for "
"the type `SomeEnum`, instead of for each variant of the type:"
msgstr ""
"有一个例外情况：如果很明显每个成员都会触发 lint 检查，那么在类型层面上期望进"
"行 lint 检查是合理的。例如，在下面的代码中，我们为类型 `SomeEnum` 添加了 "
"`#[expect(non_camel_case_types)]`，而不是为该类型的每个变体添加。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:54
msgid "When to `#[expect(dead_code)]`"
msgstr "何时需要`#[expect(dead_code)]`"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:56
msgid ""
"In general, dead code should be avoided because _(i)_ it introduces "
"unnecessary maintenance overhead, and _(ii)_ its correctness can only be "
"guaranteed by manual and error-pruned review of the code."
msgstr ""
"一般来说，应该避免无用代码，因为*（i）*它会引入不必要的维护开销，*（ii）*其正"
"确性只能通过人工且经过错误检查的代码审查来保证。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:61
msgid ""
"In the case where expecting dead code is necessary, it should fulfill the "
"following requirements:"
msgstr "如果需要预期死代码，则应满足以下要求："

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:63
msgid ""
"We have a _concrete case_ that will be implemented in the future and will "
"turn the dead code into used code."
msgstr "我们有一个*具体的案例*，将在未来实施，并将无用代码转化为可用代码。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:65
msgid ""
"The semantics of the dead code are _clear_ enough (perhaps with the help of "
"some comments), _even if the use case has not been added_."
msgstr ""
"死代码的语义已经足够*清晰*了。（或许可以借助一些注释），*即使尚未添加用例*。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:68
msgid ""
"The dead code is _simple_ enough that both the committer and the reviewer "
"can be confident that the code must be correct _without even testing it_."
msgstr ""
"这段死代码非常*简单*，提交者和审查者都可以确信代码一定是正确的 ，*甚至无需进"
"行测试*。"

#: src/to-contribute/style-guidelines/rust-guidelines.md:73
msgid ""
"For example, it is fine to add ABI constants that are unused because the "
"corresponding feature (_e.g.,_ a system call) is partially implemented. This "
"is a case where all of the above requirements are met, so adding them as "
"dead code is perfectly acceptable."
msgstr ""
"例如，如果相应的功能（*例如*系统调用）仅部分实现，则添加未使用的 ABI 常量是可"
"以接受的。这种情况满足上述所有要求，因此将其作为死代码添加是完全可以接受的。"

#: src/SUMMARY.md:98
msgid "Version Bump"
msgstr "版本号更新"

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:3
msgid "Version Numbers"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:5
msgid ""
"Currently, Asterinas regularly releases two main artifacts for the Rust OS "
"developer community: the [OSDK](https://crates.io/crates/cargo-osdk) and "
"[OSTD](https://crates.io/crates/ostd). To support development with these "
"tools, we also publish companion Docker images on DockerHub, (i.e., "
"[`asterinas/osdk`](https://hub.docker.com/r/asterinas/osdk)). While the "
"Asterinas kernel is not yet ready for public binary release, its development "
"Docker images (i.e., [`asterinas/asterinas`](https://hub.docker.com/r/"
"asterinas/asterinas)) are released regularly."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:16
msgid ""
"All released crates for OSDK and OSTD share the same version number, which "
"is stored in the `VERSION` file at the project root. The current content of "
"this file is shown below."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:24
msgid ""
"Similarly, the Docker images’ version number is stored in the "
"`DOCKER_IMAGE_VERSION` file, as shown below."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:32
msgid ""
"We use a custom format for Docker image versions: `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH-DATE`. "
"The `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH` component aligns with the target version of "
"published crates, while the `DATE` component allows us to introduce non-"
"breaking updates to the Docker images without publishing a new crate "
"version. Normally, the version in `VERSION` and the version in "
"`DOCKER_IMAGE_VERSION` (ignoring the `DATE` part) are identical, except "
"during the version bump process."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:41
msgid "How to Bump Versions"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:43
msgid "We recommend a three-commit procedure to bump versions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:44
msgid ""
"**Commit 1 \"Bump the Docker image version\"** triggers the generation of a "
"new Docker image."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:45
msgid ""
"**Commit 2 \"Switch to a new Docker image\"** makes the codebase use the new "
"Docker image."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:46
msgid ""
"**Commit 3 \"Bump the project version\"** triggers the release of new crates."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:48
msgid ""
"Depending on your exact purpose, you may complete the version bump process "
"with at most three commits within two PRs."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:50
msgid ""
"**To make non-breaking changes to the Docker images**, submit Commit 1 in a "
"PR, then Commit 2 in another."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:52
msgid ""
"**To make breaking changes to the Docker images and the crates' APIs**, "
"submit Commit 1 in a PR, then Commit 2 and 3 in another."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:55
msgid ""
"Across the three commits, you will be assisted with a convenient utility "
"script, `tools/bump_version.sh`,"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:58
msgid "Commit 1: \"Bump the Docker image version\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:60
msgid ""
"After updating the Docker image content, increment the Docker image version "
"using the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:67
msgid ""
"The second argument specifies which part of the Docker image version to "
"increment. Use `date` for non-breaking Docker image changes. If the changes "
"affect the crates intended to publish, select `major`, `minor`, or `patch` "
"in line with semantic versioning."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:72
msgid ""
"This command updates the `DOCKER_IMAGE_VERSION` file. Submit these changes "
"as a pull request. Once merged, the CI will automatically trigger the "
"creation of new Docker images."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:76
msgid "Commit 2: \"Switch to a new Docker image\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:78
msgid ""
"Creating new Docker images can be time-consuming. Once the images have been "
"pushed to DockerHub, write a follow-up commit to update all Docker image "
"version references across the codebase."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:87
msgid ""
"If your purpose is to publish non-breaking changes to the Docker images, "
"then submit this commit in a PR and then your job is finished. Otherwise, go "
"on with Commit 3."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:91
msgid "Commit 3: \"Bump the project version\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:93
msgid ""
"In this commit, synchronize the version number in `VERSION` with that in "
"`DOCKER_IMAGE_VERSION` by running:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/version-bump.md:101
msgid ""
"This command also updates all version numbers in the `Cargo.toml` files of "
"all crates scheduled for release. Pack these changes into a third commit and "
"submit the last two commits in a single PR. After the PR is merged into the "
"`main` branch, the CI will automatically publish the new crate versions."
msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:104
msgid "RFC Overview"
msgstr "RFC 概述"

#: src/rfcs/index.md:3
msgid ""
"The Asterinas RFC process is intended to provide a consistent, transparent, "
"structured path for the community to make \"big\" decisions. For example, "
"the RFC process can be used to evolve the project roadmap and the system "
"architecture."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/index.md:5
msgid "For more details, see the [RFC-0001 RFC process](0001-rfc-process.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:1
msgid "RFC-0001: RFC process"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:3
msgid "Status: Implemented"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:4
msgid "Pull request: https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2365/"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:5
msgid "Date submitted: 2025-08-24"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:6
msgid "Date approved: 2025-09-05"
msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:1
msgid "Summary"
msgstr "概览"

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:10
msgid ""
"The \"RFC\" (request for comments) process is intended to provide a "
"consistent, transparent, structured path for the community to make \"big\" "
"decisions. For example, the RFC process can be used to evolve the project "
"roadmap and the system architecture."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:12
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:14
msgid ""
"As the Asterinas project grows in scale and community size, an informal "
"decision-making process becomes insufficient. A formalized process is "
"crucial for maintaining the quality and coherence of the project. Several "
"highly successful open-source projects have demonstrated the value of such a "
"process, including Rust ([RFCs](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/"
"introduction.html)), Fuchsia ([RFCs](https://fuchsia.dev/fuchsia-src/"
"contribute/governance/rfcs)), Python ([Python Enhancement Proposals](https://"
"peps.python.org/) or PEPs), and Kubernetes ([Kubernetes Enhancement "
"Proposals](https://www.kubernetes.dev/resources/keps/) or KEPs)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:16
msgid "Adopting a formal RFC process will:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:17
msgid ""
"**Enhance decision quality**: By requiring a detailed proposal and public "
"discussion, we can ensure that decisions are well-reasoned, technically "
"sound, and consider a wide range of perspectives."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:18
msgid ""
"**Foster Consensus**: The process provides a clear framework for the "
"community to come together, discuss differing viewpoints, and arrive at a "
"consensus on important issues."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:19
msgid ""
"**Create design records**: Approved RFCs will serve as a historical archive, "
"documenting the design choices made and the reasoning behind them. This is "
"invaluable for new contributors and for future reference."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:21
msgid ""
"By introducing this process, we aim to support the healthy and sustainable "
"growth of the Asterinas project."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:23
msgid "Design"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:25
msgid "When to follow the RFC process"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:27
msgid ""
"The RFC process should be used for any \"substantial\" change to Asterinas. "
"Examples of changes that **require** an RFC include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:28
msgid ""
"Launching new top-level sub-projects of a similar significance to OSTD and "
"OSDK."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:29
msgid "Defining or significantly altering the project roadmap and goals."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:30
msgid ""
"Establishing or changing project-wide norms, such as this RFC process itself "
"or coding style guides."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:31
msgid ""
"Proposing significant architectural designs, such as the framekernel "
"architecture or safe policy injection."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:32
msgid ""
"Introducing changes that affect user-space programs, such as adding a non-"
"Linux system call or feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:34
msgid "Examples of changes that **do not** require an RFC include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:35
msgid ""
"Proposing a design whose impact is confined to a single sub-project or "
"module. If the design is significant or non-trivial, submit a design "
"proposal on Github Issues for discussion."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:36
msgid ""
"Adding well-understood features with established patterns, such as a "
"standard Linux system call or a device driver."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:37
msgid "Refactoring existing code, fixing bugs, or improving performance."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:39
msgid ""
"When in doubt, it is best to consult with the project maintainers using the "
"methods described in the next section."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:41
msgid "How the RFC process works"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:43
msgid "The RFC process consists of several distinct stages:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:45
msgid "The Socialization Stage"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:47
msgid ""
"Before investing the time to write a full RFC, it is highly recommended to "
"socialize the core idea with the community. This helps gauge interest, "
"gather early feedback, and refine the proposal. Good venues for this include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:49
msgid ""
"Starting a discussion on the project's [GitHub Discussions page](https://"
"github.com/asterinas/asterinas/discussions)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:50
msgid "Posting a \"Pre-RFC\" document to solicit more detailed feedback."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:51
msgid "Talking to key contributors, code owners, or maintainers directly."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:53
msgid ""
"Having support from at least a few other community members is a strong "
"signal that the idea is ready for a formal RFC. Additionally, having a proof-"
"of-concept implementation or identifying individuals committed to the "
"implementation can strengthen the proposal."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:55
msgid "The Draft Stage"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:57
msgid "Once you are ready to proceed, create a formal RFC document."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:58
msgid "Fork the `asterinas/asterinas` repository."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:59
msgid ""
"In [the `rfcs` directory](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/tree/main/"
"book/src/rfcs), copy `rfc-template.md` and rename it to `0000-your-rfc-title."
"md`. The `0000` is a placeholder for the RFC number, which will be assigned "
"later."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:60
msgid ""
"Fill out the template with your proposal. The template provides a solid "
"structure, but feel free to adapt it to best suit your proposal."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:62
msgid "The Iteration Stage"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:64
msgid ""
"Submit your RFC draft as a pull request to the Asterinas repository. Once "
"the PR is opened, the formal review process begins:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:65
msgid ""
"A project maintainer will be assigned as the **facilitator** for the RFC. "
"The facilitator's role is to guide the discussion, ensure it remains "
"productive, and ultimately determine when consensus has been reached."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:66
msgid ""
"All members of the community are encouraged to review the proposal and "
"provide constructive feedback through comments on the pull request."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:67
msgid ""
"The RFC author is responsible for engaging with the feedback, addressing "
"concerns, and updating the RFC text to reflect the evolving consensus."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:69
msgid "The Voting Stage"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:71
msgid ""
"When the discussion has converged and the major points of feedback have been "
"addressed, the author can request that the facilitator initiate a final vote."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:73
msgid ""
"The vote is open to all project maintainers and code owners of top-level sub-"
"projects. See the [`CODEOWNERS`](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/blob/"
"main/CODEOWNERS) file for details."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:74
msgid "Voters can express either \"approval\" or \"rejection.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:75
msgid ""
"The final decision will be based on a [rough consensus](https://en.wikipedia."
"org/wiki/Rough_consensus) as determined by the facilitator. This means that "
"while unanimous agreement is not required, any major objections must be "
"addressed."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:77
msgid "If the final decision is approval:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:78
msgid "The facilitator will assign an unique RFC number."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:79
msgid ""
"The author will update the RFC's file name with the assigned RFC number. The "
"author should also update the metadata fields of the RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:80
msgid "The facilitator will merge the pull request."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:82
msgid "The Maintenance Stage"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:84
msgid ""
"Once an RFC is approved, the proposed changes are ready for implementation. "
"When the corresponding work is completed and merged, the RFC's status is "
"updated from \"approved\" to \"implemented.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:86
msgid ""
"Approved RFCs are considered immutable historical records of design "
"decisions. As such, only minor corrective edits like fixing typos or broken "
"links are allowed."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:88
msgid ""
"Significant changes or amendments to an existing RFC must be proposed "
"through an entirely new RFC. This new proposal can also be used to formally "
"deprecate a previous RFC, in which case the original's status will be "
"updated to \"deprecated.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:90
msgid "License"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:92
msgid ""
"All RFCs submitted to the Asterinas project are licensed under [Apache "
"License, Version 2.0](https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0). This "
"license is more permissive than [the MPL license](https://www.mozilla.org/en-"
"US/MPL/) used for the Asterinas code."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:94
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:96
msgid ""
"Introducing a formal RFC process can increase the overhead for making "
"changes to the project. The process is intentionally deliberate, which may "
"slow down the pace of development for major features. There is also a risk "
"that the process could become overly bureaucratic if not managed carefully. "
"For contributors, the effort required to write a high-quality RFC and see it "
"through the review process can be significant."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:98
msgid "Prior Art and References"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:100
msgid ""
"The Asterinas RFC process is heavily inspired by the well-established "
"processes of the following two open-source projects:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:102
msgid ""
"[Rust RFC Process](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/0002-rfc-process.html): "
"The overall structure and philosophy are closely modeled on Rust's RFC "
"process."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0001-rfc-process.md:103
msgid ""
"[Fuchsia RFC Process](https://fuchsia.dev/fuchsia-src/contribute/governance/"
"rfcs/rfc_process): We have drawn on the Fuchsia process for its clear "
"definition of roles and its emphasis on transparent decision-making."
msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:106
msgid "RFC-0002: Asterinas NixOS"
msgstr "RFC-0002: Asterinas NixOS"

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:3
msgid "Status: Approved"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:4
msgid "Pull request: https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2584"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:5
msgid "Date submitted: 2025-11-14"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:6
msgid "Date approved: 2025-12-01"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:10
msgid ""
"This RFC formally proposes the establishment of an Asterinas distribution as "
"a new, top-level sub-project of Asterinas. We intend for this distribution "
"to leverage [NixOS](https://nixos.org/) due to its unparalleled "
"customizability and rich package ecosystem. Accordingly, we propose naming "
"this new sub-project **Asterinas NixOS (AsterNixOS)**."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:12
msgid "Motivations"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:14
msgid "What is a \"distro\"?"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:16
msgid ""
"In the context of operating systems (OSes), a \"distribution\" (or "
"\"distro\") typically refers to a complete OS built around a kernel, "
"complemented by userspace tools, libraries, and applications managed via a "
"package management system. A Linux distro, for example, combines the Linux "
"kernel with a rich userspace. Similarly, an Asterinas distro will pair the "
"Asterinas kernel with a comprehensive userspace environment. For the purpose "
"of this discussion, \"distro\" will refer broadly to either a Linux or "
"Asterinas-based distro."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:18
msgid "Short-term strategic advantages"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:20
msgid ""
"Achieving a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) milestone is crucial for "
"Asterinas's maturation. Reaching MVP means that Asterinas is ready for "
"evaluation by early adopters, who expect a seamless experience comparable to "
"mainstream OSes. This includes easy application installation and out-of-the-"
"box functionality. Simply providing a kernel is insufficient; we must "
"deliver a user-friendly experience, which necessitates a full-fledged distro "
"complete with an intuitive package manager."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:22
msgid ""
"Furthermore, direct control over an Asterinas distro offers a pragmatic "
"approach to addressing Linux compatibility challenges. While Asterinas is "
"committed to a high degree of Linux compatibility, achieving perfect parity "
"in the near term is impractical. A dedicated distro allows us to configure "
"or patch specific packages to circumvent reliance on advanced or bleeding-"
"edge Linux features that do not have high priority in Asterinas. This "
"significantly reduces pressure on Asterinas kernel developers to implement "
"complex features prematurely, enabling a more focused and stable development "
"roadmap."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:24
msgid ""
"Beyond external users, Asterinas developers themselves will greatly benefit "
"from a dedicated distro. Testing complex applications with intricate "
"dependencies is a significant hurdle. While \"Hello World\" or even medium-"
"sized projects like Nginx or Redis can be manually built and integrated into "
"a disk image, this approach does not scale for complex applications such as "
"Spark, PyTorch, or Chromium. Identifying, understanding, and building every "
"dependency for such projects would divert critical kernel development "
"resources. A distro, by its very nature, abstracts this complexity through "
"its package manager, streamlining the testing and development workflow for "
"all Asterinas developers."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:26
msgid "Long-term ecosystem vision"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:28
msgid ""
"Looking ahead, we envision a thriving ecosystem of Asterinas distros. This "
"initial, kernel-developer-maintained distro will serve as a vital reference "
"implementation, fostering the creation of diverse Asterinas-based distros. "
"While the Linux world boasts numerous distros, Asterinas-specific distros "
"will be essential for two primary reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:30
msgid ""
"Firstly, Asterinas prioritizes Linux compatibility at the external ABI "
"level, not the internal kernel module interface. This means Asterinas cannot "
"load Linux kernel modules (`.ko` files). An Asterinas distro will ensure "
"that all system programs exclusively load Asterinas kernel modules."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:32
msgid ""
"Secondly, Asterinas will eventually provide features and value propositions "
"that Linux simply does not have—for example, new system calls, file systems, "
"and device drivers. These benefits only become real when applications can "
"detect and leverage them."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:34
msgid ""
"An Asterinas distro is the natural vehicle for this. It can ship new "
"packages written specifically for Asterinas and carry patches to existing "
"packages to make them \"Asterinas-aware\", ensuring that userspace can "
"meaningfully take advantage of the kernel’s unique capabilities."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:36
msgid ""
"In essence, establishing Asterinas distros is paramount for Asterinas's long-"
"term success and differentiation. This RFC lays the groundwork for that "
"future by proposing our foundational distro."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:40
msgid "Why NixOS as the base distro?"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:42
msgid ""
"Building the first Asterinas distro from scratch would be an immense "
"undertaking, diverting focus from core kernel development. Therefore, basing "
"it on an existing Linux distro is the most rational path forward. This leads "
"to the crucial question: which Linux distro should serve as our foundation?"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:44
msgid ""
"The landscape of Linux distros is vast, featuring prominent names such as "
"[Arch](https://archlinux.org/), [CentOS](https://www.centos.org/), [Debian]"
"(https://www.debian.org/), and [Gentoo](https://www.gentoo.org/). While "
"theoretically, any of these could serve, we have identified [NixOS](https://"
"nixos.org/) as a particularly attractive and uniquely suited option."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:46
msgid ""
"In most distros, package recipes are centered around shell scripts (e.g., "
"[`PKGBUILD`](https://man.archlinux.org/man/PKGBUILD.5#EXAMPLE) in Arch Linux "
"or the [`rules`](https://www.debian.org/doc/manuals/maint-guide/dreq.en."
"html#rules) file in a Debian package). NixOS, however, utilizes a purpose-"
"built, purely functional language called [Nix](https://nixos-and-flakes."
"thiscute.world/the-nix-language/), which offers unparalleled expressiveness "
"and flexibility for defining package recipes."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:48
msgid ""
"A core requirement for our base distro is the ability to easily tweak "
"existing package recipes to work around Asterinas's limitations or customize "
"the new distro's look or behavior. The Nix language excels in this regard."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:50
msgid ""
"For instance, consider overriding specific attributes of an existing Nix "
"package, such as `xfdesktop`, with minimal code:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:52
msgid ""
"```nix\n"
"{ pkgs }:\n"
"{\n"
"  xfdesktop = pkgs.xfce.xfdesktop.overrideAttrs (oldAttrs: {\n"
"    version = \"4.16.0\";\n"
"    patches = (oldAttrs.patches or []) ++ [\n"
"      ./patches/xfdesktop4/0001-Fix-not-using-consistent-monitor-identifiers."
"patch\n"
"    ];\n"
"  });\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:64
msgid ""
"This Nix file creates a customized `xfdesktop` package without requiring "
"intrusive modifications to its original recipe. This capability, known as "
"[the override design pattern](https://nixos.org/guides/nix-pills/14-override-"
"design-pattern.html) in Nix, is uniquely feasible due to Nix's first-class "
"functions and lazy evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:66
msgid ""
"Another powerful example of NixOS's flexibility is how easily we can create "
"an Asterinas distro ISO installer by customizing an existing [NixOS "
"installer ISO](https://nixos.org/download/#nixos-iso). Consider the "
"following `iso-image.nix` file:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:68
msgid ""
"```nix\n"
"{ lib, pkgs, ... }:\n"
"let\n"
"  asterinas_kernel = builtins.path { path = \"asterinas_bin\"; };\n"
"  auto_install_script = pkgs.replaceVarsWith {\n"
"    src = \"./auto_install.sh\";\n"
"    isExecutable = true;\n"
"    replacements = {\n"
"      shell = \"${pkgs.bash}/bin/sh\";\n"
"      inherit asterinas_kernel;\n"
"    };\n"
"  };\n"
"  configuration = {\n"
"    imports = [\n"
"      \"${pkgs.path}/nixos/modules/installer/cd-dvd/installation-cd-minimal."
"nix\"\n"
"      \"${pkgs.path}/nixos/modules/installer/cd-dvd/channel.nix\"\n"
"    ];\n"
"\n"
"    services.getty.autologinUser = lib.mkForce \"root\";\n"
"    environment.loginShellInit = \"${auto_install_script}\";\n"
"  };\n"
"in (pkgs.nixos configuration).config.system.build.isoImage\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:92
msgid ""
"This file defines a new installer ISO that differs from the original in two "
"key ways. First, it ships with the Asterinas kernel (`asterinas_kernel`). "
"Second, instead of dropping the user into an interactive shell, the ISO's "
"init process immediately runs an automatic installation script "
"(`auto_install.sh`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:94
msgid ""
"A notable NixOS feature relevant to our design is `/etc/nixos/configuration."
"nix`, the [primary configuration file](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/"
"#sec-configuration-file) that determines _all_ system-wide states of a NixOS "
"installation, including the kernel, installed software, and configuration. A "
"minimal `configuration.nix` for our distro might look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:111
msgid ""
"Here, the sample `configuration.nix` uses a NixOS feature called [overlays]"
"(https://wiki.nixos.org/wiki/Overlays) to customize and extend Nixpkgs "
"without modifying its upstream source. Overlays apply globally within the "
"configuration, so our Asterinas-specific changes to vanilla NixOS can be "
"expressed cleanly as reusable overlays rather than as ad-hoc patches "
"scattered throughout the system."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:113
msgid ""
"A further significant advantage of NixOS is the portability of [Nix](https://"
"nixos.org/download/#nix-install-linux), its package manager (and the Nix "
"language it uses), across various Linux distros and even macOS."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:115
msgid ""
"Unlike most package managers, which are tightly coupled to their parent "
"distros (e.g., `pacman` for Arch, `dpkg` for Debian, `rpm` for Red Hat-based "
"systems), Nix operates independently. Nix packages are installed in the `/"
"nix/store` directory, ensuring they do not conflict with native packages. "
"This portability is invaluable for debugging: if a package in our NixOS-"
"based distro encounters an issue, we can replicate the exact same package "
"environment on any Linux development machine, greatly simplifying "
"troubleshooting."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:117
msgid "The New Top-Level Sub-Project"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:119
msgid ""
"Given these compelling rationales, we propose the creation of a new top-"
"level sub-project named _Asterinas NixOS (AsterNixOS)_. This sub-project "
"will reside in a new `distro/` directory at the project root."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:121
msgid ""
"Initially, AsterNixOS will share version numbers with the Asterinas kernel, "
"emphasizing its early development stage and close coupling. Every kernel "
"release will be accompanied by a compatible distro release. In the long "
"term, once both the kernel and the distro achieve maturity and stability, "
"AsterNixOS will adopt its own independent versioning scheme, likely "
"following a \"YY.MM\" format (e.g., 25.12)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:123
msgid "Drawbacks, Alternatives, and Unknowns"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:127
msgid ""
"**Learning curve for Nix/NixOS:** This is arguably the most significant "
"hurdle. While exceptionally powerful, the Nix ecosystem, including the Nix "
"language and its functional paradigm, presents a steeper learning curve "
"compared to conventional package managers and build systems. This could pose "
"an initial barrier for new contributors and existing Asterinas developers "
"unfamiliar with Nix. Investing in clear documentation and onboarding "
"resources will be critical."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:128
msgid ""
"**Maintenance overhead of Nixpkgs overlay:** While the override pattern "
"offers flexibility, maintaining a dedicated overlay for Asterinas-specific "
"patches and configurations within the vast `nixpkgs` repository will still "
"require continuous effort. Keeping pace with upstream `nixpkgs` changes, "
"resolving potential conflicts, and ensuring compatibility will be an ongoing "
"challenge requiring dedicated resources."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:130
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:132
msgid ""
"**Embedded Linux distros:** [Buildroot](https://buildroot.org/) and [Yocto]"
"(https://www.yoctoproject.org/) are established and highly capable tools for "
"building embedded Linux distros, offering extensive customization for "
"toolchains and root filesystems from scratch."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:133
msgid ""
"**Why NixOS is superior:** While powerful for embedded use cases, Buildroot "
"and Yocto are less oriented toward a general-purpose desktop/server distro, "
"which is our primary initial target. Furthermore, their configuration "
"languages are generally less expressive and composable than the Nix "
"language, limiting the flexibility we seek for deep customization and "
"elegant overriding."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:134
msgid ""
"**Direct port of Debian/Arch/etc.:** This approach would involve directly "
"modifying the build systems of a more traditional distro like Debian or Arch "
"to target Asterinas."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:135
msgid ""
"**Why NixOS is superior:** As elaborated, traditional packaging systems are "
"less flexible for the granular, targeted patching and configuration required "
"when adapting to a new kernel. More critically, their package managers (e."
"g., `dpkg`, `pacman`, `rpm`) are inherently tied to their parent distros, "
"making cross-distro development and debugging significantly more complex. "
"The Nix package manager's portability offers a clear advantage here."
msgstr ""

#: src/rfcs/0002-asterinas-nixos.md:139
msgid ""
"The NixOS project itself serves as the most prominent piece of prior art, "
"demonstrating the viability and advantages of a purely functional approach "
"to OS configuration and package management. Its design principles, "
"particularly around atomic upgrades, rollbacks, and reproducible builds, "
"have been thoroughly proven since its inception in 2003. Other projects, "
"like [GNU Guix](https://guix.gnu.org/), also follow a similar functional "
"package management paradigm."
msgstr ""

